```javascript
function factorial(n) {
  if (n <= 1) {
    return 1;
  }
  return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

console.log(factorial(5)); // Outputs: 120
```

This is the essence of recursion. The function repeatedly calls itself with a smaller argument until it reaches a base case. Each call stacks on top of the last. When `factorial(5)` gets called, it becomes `5 * factorial(4)`, which breaks down into `5 * (4 * factorial(3))`, and so on until the smallest problem (factorial(1)) is solved.
